1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,851
Doctors use setbacks to pave the way to better health and longer life.

2
00:00:05,120 --> 00:00:12,050
Often, when a patient dies for an uncertain reason, doctors perform a post-mortem to find out why.

3
00:00:12,401 --> 00:00:19,091
In this way, they learn more about the functioning of the human body, and lives of other people are saved.

4
00:00:20,401 --> 00:00:29,810
A sales executive friend of mine devotes one entire sales meeting a month to helping his salesman discover why they lost important sales.

5
00:00:30,081 --> 00:00:33,891
The lost sale is reconstructed and carefully examined.

6
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:39,571
In this way, the salesman learns how to avoid losing similar sales in the future.

7
00:00:40,401 --> 00:00:48,691
The football coach who wins more games than he loses goes over the details of each game with his team to point out their mistakes.

8
00:00:49,120 --> 00:00:55,010
Some coaches have movies made of each game so the team can literally see its bad moves.

9
00:00:55,201 --> 00:00:56,051
The purpose?

10
00:00:56,081 --> 00:00:58,291
To play the next game better.

11
00:00:59,521 --> 00:01:09,171
CAA officials, successful sales executives, physicians, football coaches, and professionals in every field follow this success principle.

12
00:01:09,441 --> 00:01:12,530
Salvage something from every setback.

13
00:01:13,441 --> 00:01:22,211
When a setback hits us personally, our first impulse is often to become so emotionally upset that we fail to learn the lesson.

14
00:01:22,721 --> 00:01:29,411
Professors know that a student's reaction to a failing grade provides a clue to his success potential.

15
00:01:29,920 --> 00:01:34,931
When I was a professor at Wayne State University in Detroit some years ago,

16
00:01:35,041 --> 00:01:39,811
I had no choice but to turn in a failing grade for a graduating senior.

17
00:01:40,081 --> 00:01:42,291
This was a real blow to the student.

18
00:01:42,401 --> 00:01:47,250
He had already made graduation plans, and canceling was embarrassing.

19
00:01:47,521 --> 00:01:54,691
He was left with two alternatives, retake and pass the course, and receive his degree at a later graduation,

20
00:01:54,801 --> 00:01:57,571
or quit school without earning a degree.

21
00:01:58,641 --> 00:02:05,331
I expected that the student would be disappointed, perhaps even somewhat belligerent, when he learned of his setback.

22
00:02:05,601 --> 00:02:06,691
I was right.

23
00:02:07,041 --> 00:02:16,531
After I explained that his work was far below passing standards, the student admitted that he hadn't put forth a serious effort in the course.

24
00:02:17,281 --> 00:02:21,250
But, he continued, my past record is at least average.

25
00:02:21,361 --> 00:02:22,931
Can't you consider that?

26
00:02:23,601 --> 00:02:29,171
I pointed out that I could not, because we measure performance one course at a time.

27
00:02:29,521 --> 00:02:37,889
I added that rigid academic codes prohibited changing grades for any reason other than an honest mistake on the part of the professor.

28
00:02:38,481 --> 00:02:45,091
Then the student, realizing that all avenues toward a grade change were closed, became quite angry.

29
00:02:45,441 --> 00:02:54,610
Professor, he said, I could name 50 people in this city who've succeeded in a big way without taking this course or even knowing about it.

30
00:02:54,881 --> 00:02:57,890
What's so blasted important about this course?

31
00:02:58,001 --> 00:03:02,610
Why should a few bad marks in one course keep me from getting my degree?

32
00:03:03,121 --> 00:03:08,610
Thank God, he added, they don't look at things on the outside like you professors do.

33
00:03:09,601 --> 00:03:13,731
After that remark, I paused for about 45 seconds.

34
00:03:14,081 --> 00:03:22,245
I've learned that when you've been sniped at, one fine way to prevent a war of words is to take a long pause before answering.
